  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Which are the best airplane seats in economy class?",
  "response": "The best airplane seats in economy class can vary based on personal preferences, but here are some general tips to help you choose:\n\n1. **Window Seats**: If you enjoy the view and want to lean against the wall to sleep, choose a window seat. These seats are typically numbered A or F (e.g., 20A, 20F).\n\n2. **Aisle Seats**: If you need to stretch your legs or get up frequently, an aisle seat might be best. These are usually labeled C or D (e.g., 20C, 20D).\n\n3. **Front of the Cabin**: Seats closer to the front of the economy section often allow you to disembark more quickly and may be further from the lavatories, reducing noise and smells. They are also usually closer to the galley, which can be both a pro (easier to get service) and a con (more noise during meal service).\n\n4. **Exit Rows**: These seats often have more legroom but may come with some restrictions, such as not being able to store items under the seat in front of you. They can be a good choice for taller passengers.\n\n5. **Avoid the Middle**: Middle seats (usually B or E, e.g., 20B, 20E) are generally considered the least desirable due to being sandwiched between two other passengers.\n\n6. **Bulkhead Seats**: These are the seats directly behind a wall or divider. They often have more legroom but may have issues with bassinets or less storage space for personal items.\n\n7. **Check Seat Maps**: Websites like SeatGuru allow you to input your flight details and get specific advice on the best and worst seats for your particular aircraft.\n\nUltimately, the \"best\" seat depends on your priorities\u2014whether that's extra legroom, easy access to the aisle, or a good view out the window.",
